233
00:14:56,195 --> 00:14:58,325
does it just hide more complexity?

234
00:14:58,825 --> 00:15:03,445
When this breaks at 3:00 AM will it help
the on-call engineer learn something

235
00:15:03,445 --> 00:15:08,155
about how our systems work, or will
it leave them even more confused?

236
00:15:08,655 --> 00:15:11,535
To make this simple, there's
a three question framework.

237
00:15:12,035 --> 00:15:16,415
Before you build your next
abstraction, ask these three questions.

238
00:15:16,415 --> 00:15:17,585
'cause it will really help.

239
00:15:18,085 --> 00:15:22,195
Can I trace through this when
something goes wrong, can I follow the

240
00:15:22,195 --> 00:15:25,495
breadcrumbs to understand what happened?

241
00:15:25,995 --> 00:15:27,285
Does this teach me something?

242
00:15:27,675 --> 00:15:30,645
Am I learning about a system
through using this tool, or am I

243
00:15:30,645 --> 00:15:32,955
just following a rooted procedure?

244
00:15:33,455 --> 00:15:34,655
Can I graduate?

245
00:15:34,655 --> 00:15:39,785
My understanding is there a natural
path from basic usage to deep system.

246
00:15:39,785 --> 00:15:45,415
Understanding the future of reliable
systems isn't about hiding complexity.

247
00:15:45,475 --> 00:15:48,235
It's about making it
approachable and manageable.

248
00:15:48,735 --> 00:15:53,690
Abstractions should be bridges to
understanding not solid walls around it.

249
00:15:54,190 --> 00:15:57,370
The best abstractions that we
see don't just solve problems.

250
00:15:57,430 --> 00:16:00,250
They help transfer knowledge
and build capability.

251
00:16:01,150 --> 00:16:05,110
Whether this is building tools,
contributing to open source or

252
00:16:05,110 --> 00:16:10,360
designing processes, focus on systems
like we did that scale operationally.

253
00:16:11,050 --> 00:16:13,810
This is where knowledge grows
alongside the technology.

254
00:16:14,310 --> 00:16:17,745
If you have any questions, there's a QR
code for you to scan at the end here.

255
00:16:18,435 --> 00:16:22,245
You can always send me questions, but
I'm always happy to answer questions

256
00:16:22,245 --> 00:16:24,615
about building systems that truly scale.

257
00:16:25,115 --> 00:16:28,535
I hope you've enjoyed this presentation
and look forward to seeing you soon.

